WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.000
I'm going to tell you two things in this talk.

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:13.480
First, how you can build accessible lessons with the Carpentries Workbench.

00:00:13.480 --> 00:00:18.959
And second, how we used R to build the Carpentries Workbench, which allowed us to transform our

00:00:18.959 --> 00:00:26.200
lessons from looking like this to looking something a bit more like this.

00:00:26.200 --> 00:00:31.400
And I have a lot of people that I need to thank for this talk, including the RStudio

00:00:31.400 --> 00:00:37.119
Diversity Scholars Program, which brought myself and soon-to-be Dr. Sharon Hurt to this

00:00:37.119 --> 00:00:41.400
conference, but I don't really have the time to go over this.

00:00:41.400 --> 00:00:47.320
And what you need to know about this talk is that you need to know who the Carpentries

00:00:47.320 --> 00:00:49.400
are in order to appreciate it.

00:00:49.400 --> 00:00:53.560
In order to understand who the Carpentries are, I'm going to tell you a little story

00:00:53.560 --> 00:00:55.540
about myself.

00:00:55.540 --> 00:00:56.580
This is not a recent photo.

00:00:56.580 --> 00:00:58.459
This was from 2014.

00:00:58.459 --> 00:01:04.860
I was teaching my very first conference workshop in Population Genetics in R, giving it to

00:01:04.860 --> 00:01:05.860
plant pathologists.

00:01:05.860 --> 00:01:12.400
If you're wondering what Population Genetics in R is, think 23andMe, but for fungi.

00:01:12.400 --> 00:01:19.019
So in this workshop, I wrote the materials all in R Markdown.

00:01:19.019 --> 00:01:26.300
I forced my advisor to use Git and ended up fixing a lot of merge conflicts, and the

00:01:26.300 --> 00:01:30.519
process of building this was very painful.

00:01:30.519 --> 00:01:34.220
It was very much close your eyes and hope it works.

00:01:34.220 --> 00:01:42.379
I did end up building the website, but that version of me knew quite a lot about Population

00:01:42.379 --> 00:01:47.820
Genetics, knew quite a lot about plant pathology, didn't know very much about inclusive teaching,

00:01:47.820 --> 00:01:54.500
custom design, or live coding, and this workshop, it was actually successful.

00:01:54.500 --> 00:01:57.900
We ran it for two years, got really good reviews.

00:01:57.900 --> 00:02:01.739
People liked it, but something was really bothering me.

00:02:01.739 --> 00:02:04.580
Something was eating me on the inside.

00:02:04.580 --> 00:02:08.419
I didn't actually know what people learned.

00:02:08.419 --> 00:02:09.899
I knew they learned something.

00:02:09.899 --> 00:02:10.899
They had their computers open.

00:02:10.899 --> 00:02:15.820
They were following along, but I don't know what they learned, and here's the thing.

00:02:15.820 --> 00:02:18.300
My advisor had no way of supporting me in that.

00:02:18.300 --> 00:02:21.619
He was a government scientist.

00:02:21.619 --> 00:02:28.619
He hadn't taught a course in years, and so if I had a way to get the support I needed,

00:02:28.619 --> 00:02:36.779
such as maybe a template that could have given me the narrative elements and elements for

00:02:36.779 --> 00:02:41.580
formative assessment, I would have been able to succeed in understanding what my learners

00:02:41.580 --> 00:02:48.139
learned and then improve that lesson over time, and I know now that the Carpentries

00:02:48.139 --> 00:02:56.179
provides that support and gives a safe space for improving my teaching, and the Carpentries

00:02:56.179 --> 00:03:01.860
is all about spreading data science skills to researchers around the globe to really

00:03:01.860 --> 00:03:09.940
democratize access to data, and it does this by fostering communities of practice, and

00:03:10.059 --> 00:03:16.740
these are volunteers who are trained in evidence-based teaching principles from all around the world,

00:03:16.740 --> 00:03:23.820
and we all come together through shared core values in that we are motivated in that we

00:03:23.820 --> 00:03:27.660
are always learning and we're inclusive of all.

00:03:27.660 --> 00:03:29.779
In practice, we act openly.

00:03:29.779 --> 00:03:37.059
We empower one another, and we value all contributions, which allows us to achieve our goals of championing

00:03:37.059 --> 00:03:44.419
people first, access for all, community collaboration, and strength through diversity, and we know

00:03:44.419 --> 00:03:53.940
that it works because we have led over 3,500 workshops in the past 10 years to over 60

00:03:53.940 --> 00:04:04.139
countries, 3,900 instructors, 45 lessons to over 80,000 novice learners in over 90 member

00:04:04.139 --> 00:04:05.139
institutions.

00:04:05.220 --> 00:04:12.179
So it's a lot of number, but the key to this, the reason why this works is because our instructors

00:04:12.179 --> 00:04:14.179
never teach alone.

00:04:14.179 --> 00:04:19.700
In a Carpentries workshop, if you are an instructor, if you're a new instructor, you're always

00:04:19.700 --> 00:04:25.779
paired with someone who's taught this before, and this is always possible because of the

00:04:25.779 --> 00:04:32.420
efforts of our director of workshops, Sharon Hurt, who allows you, who gives you the opportunity

00:04:32.420 --> 00:04:38.420
to teach these workshops, and these workshops would not be possible without our open source

00:04:38.420 --> 00:04:44.019
and open license materials that are available on GitHub, and it's these materials that I'm

00:04:44.019 --> 00:04:49.380
going to talk about for the rest of the talk because these have a long history.

00:04:49.380 --> 00:04:54.459
They were originally written in HTML, just straight HTML.

00:04:54.459 --> 00:05:01.100
Really difficult to write if you're not, if you're really tired or, yeah.

00:05:01.100 --> 00:05:07.100
Eventually they switched over to Jekyll, which is GitHub's default site generator,

00:05:07.100 --> 00:05:11.260
and I'm going to ask for a little audience participation here, okay?

00:05:11.260 --> 00:05:14.380
So I'm going to ask you three questions.

00:05:14.380 --> 00:05:19.019
If the answer is yes, I want you to clap twice, okay?

00:05:19.019 --> 00:05:20.019
With me?

00:05:20.019 --> 00:05:26.339
So first question, just to get a baseline, if you have ever used Jekyll, clap twice.

00:05:26.339 --> 00:05:28.380
Okay, good.

00:05:28.380 --> 00:05:35.059
If you have ever uttered a curse word while using Jekyll, clap twice.

00:05:35.059 --> 00:05:37.459
That was about the same, okay.

00:05:37.459 --> 00:05:43.220
If you have ever wanted to set your laptop on fire while using Jekyll, please, clap twice.

00:05:43.220 --> 00:05:44.459
Okay.

00:05:44.459 --> 00:05:53.880
So yeah, Jekyll's kind of hard to use, and the thing is, it's been shown as a barrier.

00:05:53.880 --> 00:05:58.600
When you're just trying to build a lesson, when you're trying to work on a lesson, you

00:05:58.600 --> 00:06:07.640
just want to fix a typo, you want to update an image, and you find this, you really want

00:06:07.640 --> 00:06:09.640
to burn it all down.

00:06:09.640 --> 00:06:14.859
It's not easy to use, and the thing is, it wasn't living up to our values.

00:06:14.859 --> 00:06:16.540
This really did not put people first.

00:06:16.540 --> 00:06:19.920
This was putting the machines first.

00:06:19.920 --> 00:06:24.720
And so I was hired in 2020 to reimagine this infrastructure, because it was clear it was

00:06:24.720 --> 00:06:27.200
not living up to our values.

00:06:27.200 --> 00:06:34.000
And what I realized is that we really need to separate the tools from the content.

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:40.000
Anything everybody should worry about is just being able to write markdown, or R markdown,

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:46.480
and get a website out of it, and not having to sift through all the output that's contained

00:06:46.559 --> 00:06:51.399
in the same folder, or having to worry about tools breaking.

00:06:51.399 --> 00:06:58.739
And so this is how I created the Carpentries Workbench, and this is a series of packages

00:06:58.739 --> 00:07:04.239
that avoids having a lesson being wrapped around a blog infrastructure, and it keeps

00:07:04.239 --> 00:07:09.959
the tools and outputs separate, and it's based on the philosophy of package down.

00:07:09.959 --> 00:07:12.600
Work where you are.

00:07:12.600 --> 00:07:16.760
And this, it consists of three packages.

00:07:16.760 --> 00:07:20.480
The first package that you're going to interact with is sandpaper.

00:07:20.480 --> 00:07:22.119
This is what orchestrates everything.

00:07:22.119 --> 00:07:25.920
The only command you really need to know is sandpaper serve.

00:07:25.920 --> 00:07:31.920
The next package is on the inside, and you don't interact with it so often, but you do

00:07:31.920 --> 00:07:38.880
with it, you do, sandpaper uses it in the backend to help you validate your markdown,

00:07:38.880 --> 00:07:43.440
to make sure that it actually is going to do what you want it to do.

00:07:43.440 --> 00:07:46.119
And then coming in at the end is varnish.

00:07:46.119 --> 00:07:51.480
That gives you the styling of your lessons, to make sure that your lessons are accessible

00:07:51.480 --> 00:07:53.920
and beautiful.

00:07:53.920 --> 00:07:59.859
And all of this was designed with what I like to call core values-driven design.

00:07:59.859 --> 00:08:04.279
And so I'm going to talk about a few of our core values and how the design elements fit

00:08:04.279 --> 00:08:05.920
in with them.

00:08:05.920 --> 00:08:09.480
There are a lot more, but I don't have that much time.

00:08:09.480 --> 00:08:13.799
So the first thing I'm going to start with is championing people first, because really

00:08:13.799 --> 00:08:20.420
individuals who make up our community are the most important part of our organization.

00:08:20.420 --> 00:08:22.399
And they are our strongest resource.

00:08:22.399 --> 00:08:28.160
So it only makes sense that when I was looking for a static site generator, something to

00:08:28.160 --> 00:08:34.559
generate our websites with, that I would choose something that had the most on ramps.

00:08:34.559 --> 00:08:39.799
And really, R is the best resource.

00:08:39.799 --> 00:08:42.659
It makes the most sense.

00:08:42.659 --> 00:08:46.760
You saw it in Ileana's talk, and you see it here.

00:08:46.760 --> 00:08:51.440
And this tweet from Janita Bellini, and she says that some people laugh when I tell them

00:08:51.440 --> 00:08:57.159
that R's best feature as a language is its community, but I'm very serious.

00:08:57.159 --> 00:09:02.320
Especially Rladies has been such a positive agent of change for so many people.

00:09:03.159 --> 00:09:05.960
That's one of the reasons why y'all are here.

00:09:05.960 --> 00:09:08.000
We are a good community here.

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:11.219
We know how to make people feel included.

00:09:11.219 --> 00:09:14.520
And so it only makes sense.

00:09:14.520 --> 00:09:19.679
Another way that we're championing people first is that we virtually increase the number

00:09:19.679 --> 00:09:22.840
of instructors in the room when you're teaching a lesson.

00:09:22.840 --> 00:09:25.039
And I'm going to explain what I mean by that.

00:09:25.039 --> 00:09:26.640
So you have your lesson.

00:09:26.640 --> 00:09:28.200
It has code examples.

00:09:28.200 --> 00:09:32.840
And you want to teach someone how to add a column to a data frame.

00:09:32.840 --> 00:09:33.840
Okay?

00:09:33.840 --> 00:09:39.239
So you are working in RStudio, and you show them the code, you run the code, and then

00:09:39.239 --> 00:09:41.880
you have output that looks like this.

00:09:41.880 --> 00:09:45.880
You can't really tell what happened, because there are so many columns in the data frame,

00:09:45.880 --> 00:09:48.119
everything ran off the edge.

00:09:48.119 --> 00:09:54.799
If you had the wisdom of the instructors who came before you, and yes, you are teaching

00:09:54.799 --> 00:09:55.799
with another instructor.

00:09:55.799 --> 00:09:59.119
They may know this, but they may not.

00:09:59.119 --> 00:10:04.679
You would know that you have to add a select command.

00:10:04.679 --> 00:10:12.239
And so what we do is we allow instructors to communicate through time and space by allowing

00:10:12.239 --> 00:10:19.080
them to include instructor notes directly into the lessons in the context that is needed.

00:10:19.080 --> 00:10:24.440
So that when you teach this lesson, you can change your behavior, and you can show the

00:10:24.440 --> 00:10:30.280
learners what exactly they need to know and reduce their cognitive load.

00:10:30.280 --> 00:10:35.640
And another way we champion people first is that we include automation.

00:10:35.640 --> 00:10:41.280
Oftentimes, as you're building R Markdown, packages will update.

00:10:41.280 --> 00:10:42.280
Things fail.

00:10:42.280 --> 00:10:43.280
You get a lot of errors.

00:10:43.280 --> 00:10:49.400
You get warnings that don't make sense, because the package authors changed their packages.

00:10:49.400 --> 00:10:59.200
We avoid this by embedding REMV on the back end of sandpaper.

00:10:59.200 --> 00:11:03.280
And the beauty about this, you don't need to know anything about REMV in order to use

00:11:03.280 --> 00:11:04.479
this.

00:11:04.479 --> 00:11:05.659
We lock the packages.

00:11:05.659 --> 00:11:12.200
We give you a way to update them, and we give you a way to pin them so that your lessons

00:11:12.200 --> 00:11:18.520
are always working and you have a way to investigate what happens when packages update.

00:11:18.520 --> 00:11:22.679
And I'm going to show you some of that a little bit later.

00:11:22.679 --> 00:11:30.000
And really, this leads me into the fact that we champion access for all, because it shouldn't

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:32.520
matter what packages you have on your system.

00:11:32.520 --> 00:11:35.619
It shouldn't matter what packages you have in your global library.

00:11:35.619 --> 00:11:40.299
You should be able to build the lesson the same anyone else can build the lesson.

00:11:40.299 --> 00:11:47.280
And so I'm going to show you, like, what happens when you don't have your own computer,

00:11:47.280 --> 00:11:50.719
when you're not on your own computer and you receive a pull request.

00:11:50.719 --> 00:11:53.780
That changes a plot.

00:11:53.780 --> 00:11:57.820
But can anybody tell me what's going to happen when this happens?

00:11:57.820 --> 00:11:58.979
Probably not.

00:11:58.979 --> 00:12:01.179
Because it's R code.

00:12:01.179 --> 00:12:05.659
But seeing the output of the plot is night and day.

00:12:05.659 --> 00:12:14.500
And we have embedded pull request previews for the intermediate markdown for these lessons

00:12:14.500 --> 00:12:21.619
so that you can confirm that things actually work, whether or not you have the tools installed.

00:12:21.619 --> 00:12:24.900
And this is...

00:12:24.900 --> 00:12:32.299
And furthermore, if you're writing an R lesson, sometimes you may forget to include alternative

00:12:32.299 --> 00:12:37.739
text or you have link descriptions that don't actually describe anything.

00:12:37.739 --> 00:12:39.979
And you say, whoops.

00:12:39.979 --> 00:12:52.500
And it's this kind of preflight validation that's done by Pegboard that allows you to

00:12:52.500 --> 00:12:57.140
take a step back and say, yeah, I made a mistake, and fix it.

00:12:57.140 --> 00:12:59.840
And that's really the key to...

00:12:59.840 --> 00:13:05.380
That's really the key to how we're championing access for all, and we're always learning.

00:13:05.380 --> 00:13:07.099
Because we're humans.

00:13:07.099 --> 00:13:09.260
We forget things.

00:13:09.260 --> 00:13:10.260
You shouldn't be punished.

00:13:10.260 --> 00:13:16.340
You shouldn't have, like, glaring errors when you miss something.

00:13:16.340 --> 00:13:19.140
When you mistype something.

00:13:19.140 --> 00:13:21.260
And it shows that we're always learning.

00:13:21.260 --> 00:13:23.179
And I'm going to turn it on myself.

00:13:23.179 --> 00:13:25.059
I'm always learning.

00:13:25.059 --> 00:13:27.020
Sandpaper is not the fastest thing in the world.

00:13:27.020 --> 00:13:30.539
The Workbench is not the fastest thing in the world.

00:13:30.539 --> 00:13:37.979
But I really want to address the pink pachyderm in the premises.

00:13:37.979 --> 00:13:40.619
We don't use Quarto yet.

00:13:40.619 --> 00:13:42.539
Sorry.

00:13:42.539 --> 00:13:50.000
But the way I designed the system, we're going to include Quarto in the future.

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:53.340
We just need to get it stable in our system.

00:13:53.340 --> 00:13:55.099
And I built it to be flexible.

00:13:55.179 --> 00:14:01.419
So it works on the exact same principle that Quarto works.

00:14:01.419 --> 00:14:05.859
And then finally, I want to get to the fact that we empower one another.

00:14:05.859 --> 00:14:11.739
The Workbench is going to support 168 lessons come January.

00:14:11.739 --> 00:14:17.900
And this is really key, because most of these lessons are in the Carpentries Incubator,

00:14:17.900 --> 00:14:25.900
in which people are actively developing lessons, working on lessons, testing them out, teaching

00:14:25.900 --> 00:14:31.140
them, and getting feedback and revamping them in this iterative development cycle that eventually

00:14:31.140 --> 00:14:34.340
leads to peer review of lessons.

00:14:34.340 --> 00:14:41.659
And this is the Carpentries Workbench makes this model sustainable.

00:14:41.659 --> 00:14:46.940
It makes it much easier for people to do these iterations with all of these safeguards that

00:14:46.940 --> 00:14:49.340
we've built into it.

00:14:49.340 --> 00:14:58.219
And so it's here that I want to show you that I'm not the only one who thinks this.

00:14:58.219 --> 00:15:01.179
I'm not the only one who claims this.

00:15:01.179 --> 00:15:07.359
Saba Ferdas from UCL, she's part of the Learn to Discover project.

00:15:07.359 --> 00:15:12.780
She forked sandpaper and made it run Python.

00:15:12.780 --> 00:15:17.419
And she says that it was very trivial and efficient to write custom lessons with the

00:15:17.419 --> 00:15:18.419
Carpentries Workbench.

00:15:18.419 --> 00:15:19.419
I have a link there.

00:15:19.419 --> 00:15:20.419
My slides are online.

00:15:20.419 --> 00:15:23.340
I'll give you a QR code for that.

00:15:23.340 --> 00:15:25.739
Toby Hodges, he's the curriculum lead of the Carpentries.

00:15:25.739 --> 00:15:30.219
He works with the community, and he says the Carpentries Workbench has made it easier for

00:15:30.219 --> 00:15:38.059
people to write, maintain, and teach lessons in many different ways, sometimes quite profoundly.

00:15:38.059 --> 00:15:42.099
Sarah Stevens, very embedded in the Carpentries, and she says, I'm really excited to be able

00:15:42.419 --> 00:15:47.820
to use the Workbench's accessibility features, because she's tired of not having reminders

00:15:47.820 --> 00:15:50.619
to add alt text.

00:15:50.619 --> 00:15:57.580
And finally, Francois Michonneau has been working with the Workbench since the beginning,

00:15:57.580 --> 00:16:01.340
and he says you only have to focus on writing content, and the Workbench takes care of the

00:16:01.340 --> 00:16:03.340
rest.

00:16:03.340 --> 00:16:11.179
And so here's a link that you can use, and you can create your own lesson using the Workbench.

00:16:11.260 --> 00:16:16.099
And now you can build your own accessible lesson using R.

00:16:16.099 --> 00:16:19.020
But that's not what the talk title is, y'all.

00:16:19.020 --> 00:16:20.020
Okay?

00:16:20.020 --> 00:16:23.280
What about friends, huh?

00:16:23.280 --> 00:16:28.539
This is Building Accessible Lessons with R and Friends, and this is where I put in a

00:16:28.539 --> 00:16:30.900
plug for the Carpentries.

00:16:30.900 --> 00:16:34.979
I want y'all to get involved, because really, we are a great community.

00:16:34.979 --> 00:16:40.580
There are plenty of ways to be involved in the Carpentries, and it's really a community

00:16:40.580 --> 00:16:41.859
of practice.

00:16:41.859 --> 00:16:48.960
You get so many opportunities to interact with people who really care about teaching.

00:16:48.960 --> 00:16:51.140
You can become an instructor.

00:16:51.140 --> 00:16:56.900
Next summer, we're going to open up applications for maintenance of our lessons.

00:16:56.900 --> 00:17:02.700
You can teach, create, contribute to, or review a lesson, or even just take our materials.

00:17:02.700 --> 00:17:04.819
They're completely open.

00:17:04.819 --> 00:17:11.060
Or if you're part of an organization, you can have that organization enroll as a member

00:17:11.060 --> 00:17:17.380
and use that to build your own community in your organization.

00:17:17.380 --> 00:17:25.640
And if you want to know more, we have a conference that's happening right after this conference.

00:17:25.640 --> 00:17:31.099
It's online, and we have an accessibility fund, if you want to donate to it, to make

00:17:31.099 --> 00:17:39.579
sure that we have money for translators, money for people who do captioning.

00:17:39.579 --> 00:17:44.739
And it's free to attend, so if you want to learn more, please attend.

00:17:44.739 --> 00:17:45.739
I have my slides.

00:17:45.739 --> 00:17:49.939
I have information about the Workbench, and I'd be happy to take any questions if I have

00:17:49.939 --> 00:17:50.939
time.

00:17:50.939 --> 00:17:51.939
Okay.

00:17:51.939 --> 00:17:52.939
Thank you.

00:17:52.939 --> 00:17:52.939


